<subSubSection id="4B1A8620AA2FAF865D735C1D1EAD5383" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="3C87CA1CDCCE89E3F3F0C76EAFE52D35" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName id="DE3039A3C69684CBD1BA42F43D471A71" LSID="AD4125BA-1160-51CA-9D0E-3E6F18279CE6" authority="(Burm. f.) Juss. ex Schult. (= Aerva persica (Burm. f.) Merr.)" baseAuthorityName="Burm. f.) Juss. ex Schult. (= Aerva persica (Burm. f.) Merr." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Aerva" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aerva javanica" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="javanica">Aerva javanica (Burm.f.) Juss. ex Schult. (= Aerva persica (Burm.f.) Merr.)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2D40AFB6FB3F679A648ACFC4A22677E1" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="names">
<paragraph id="3446CE88FB889C0F3302FA83621BC9F6" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0A86A017555E23599E592970524D1A6F" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="618B6742C8C2848CDD95E923BF1DF8D7" bold="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis id="5F306201995D8A2CA19B61FA5EEF1411" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">on-hnye</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B2286937C9A91CBD3445EB408A8D365A" bold="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">English</emphasis>
: aerva, kapok bush, snow bush.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7EE22663149AE1B3962A4AAF15342107" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="range">
<paragraph id="E58ED6E2A2C124B474F60AA24F811164" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="862A03E95635B2277C5674BB4294AD74" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Widespread in drier parts of the tropics and subtropics of the Old World, from Myanmar, India and Sri Lanka westwards through Southwest Asia, across North Africa to Morocco and south to Cape Verde island and Cameroun Uganda and Tanzania to Madagascar. Introduced in Australia and elsewhere.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="53C5AD63EEB95386F3D509CBBB0C7498" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="use">
<paragraph id="3C77255A35EE8EFAD43BC3404DCA953C" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Use.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A7B64099D982252C7F35056B1A843622" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="910290AD97B0894D0C66ED5FB2ABD6F3" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Root</emphasis>
: Paste made and applied to acne-like conditions of the face.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="110A1272E88638CAAF2C904035286910" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="notes">
<paragraph id="7BD11BD15CB9693610ABD53661E226E9" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D67A5A698106FC4199F4CE6F2230FD44" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The species is used as a uricant (
<bibRefCitation id="4BA9642C33670AE39252D8D1C58E8F3F" author="Burkill, HM" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Museum Leaflets, Harvard University" pageId="172" pageNumber="173" refId="B18" refString="Burkill, HM, 1985. The Useful Plants of West Tropical Africa. 2nd Edition. Volume 1, Families A-D. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." title="The Useful Plants of West Tropical Africa. 2 nd Edition. Volume 1, Families A-D. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." year="1985">Burkill 1985</bibRefCitation>
); also to treat kidney stones and for inflammation (
<bibRefCitation id="71B5B243FD97A20FA6175550FC3F7AF6" author="Zafar, M" journalOrPublisher="Brazilian Journal of Medical and Biological Research" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" publicationUrl="http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/ebl/vol2006/iss1/14/" refId="B142" refString="Zafar, M, Ahmad, M, Khan, MA, Abbas, A, 2006. Pollen pictorial of some medicinal plants from Pakistan. Ethnobotanical Leaflets 10: 121-128. http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/ebl/vol2006/iss1/14/" title="Pollen pictorial of some medicinal plants from Pakistan. Ethnobotanical Leaflets 10: 121 - 128." url="http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/ebl/vol2006/iss1/14/" year="2006">Zafar et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The medicinal uses of another member of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="9DBD9CF263C89E947353D4AA9335E6CC" authorityName="Forsskal" authorityYear="1775" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Aerva" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aerva" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AA15DDC436AC7C83E27A820D6BC48A16" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aerva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in India are discussed in 
<bibRefCitation id="00CEDCB90AEB2997134BCE6A7D691B87" author="Jain, SK" journalOrPublisher="Phytotherapy Research" pageId="173" pageNumber="174" refId="B50" refString="Jain, SK, DeFilipps, RA, 1991. Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." title="Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." year="1991">Jain and DeFilipps (1991)</bibRefCitation>
as follows: The whole plant is used for albumin in the urine; infant diarrhea; cholera; and dysentery. The leaf is used for earache; and the root is used for snakebite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
